                {"src": "ellicott", "attr": "Ellicott's Commentary", "html": "<p>Not because we find no mention of the parents of Melchizedek is he thus spoken of as fatherless and motherless, but because he is suddenly introduced as priest, without any token whatever that he held the office by right of genealogy, the only claim familiar to Hebrew readers.</p>"},
